@node MAIN_KEY "PuzzleBOBS guide - Function keys"

Function keys
-------------

Keys during menu stage:

  You can move vertically the bubble in the left menu's side using arrow keys "UP" and "DOWN".
  By "RETURN" or arrow key "RIGHT" you can switch the menu item choices, you can enter in a sub
page or execute a menu voice function.
  Using "DEL" key you come back from a sub page or exit from game to Workbench if you were in the
main menu page.


Keys during game stage:

  By pressing "p" key you enter in pause mode. During the pause PuzzleBOBS releases all the
allocated devices, as audio channels, remaps the screen's palette if you was playing in window.
  To enter in game again press "p", PuzzleBOBS will try to allocate again all resources.
  Is possible to stop the music and choose another one from a file requester by "F6".
  When that music module finishes PuzzleBOBS will jump to the next one if "Play mod = Sequence",
continue with the same if "Play mod = Only one", sort randomly its if "Play mod = Random".
  By "F7" you can stop the current music and skip to the next depending the sort method choosed by
the "Play mod" option.
  Pressing "ESC" you return to the menu.
  By "F9" you can get in ram: a file named "PuzzleBOBS_grab" which is a screen grab taken when
you press the key.
  The format of that file is:

  >For VGA modes.
   Chunky one byte per pixel is the screen has less or 256 colours ( <= ), or chunky 4 bytes per 
   pixel (0RGB) if the screen has more than 256 colours ( > ).

  >For standard Amiga modes.
   Raw interleaved.

  The procedure can busy the system a lot, above all if the screen you want grab has big resolutions,
so wait some seconds.
  You will get in ram: the palette also, named "PuzzleBOBS_grabpalette", its format is compatible
with the graphics.library LoadRGB32() function in 8 bit depth.


  Player 1 could be controlled using keyboard keys:

 - Arrow UP      You move the pointer arrow to 90 trigonometrics.
 - Arrow LEFT    You move the pointer arrow to left.
 - Arrow RIGTH   You move the pointer arrow to rigth.
 - Arrow DOWN    You move the pointer arrow to rigth if the angle is <= to 90, else to left.
 - SPACE	     Launch the bubble.


  Player 2 could be controlled using numeric pad keys:

 - Arrow UP	     You move the pointer arrow to 90 trigonometrics.
 - Arrow LEFT    You move the pointer arrow to left.
 - Arrow RIGTH   You move the pointer arrow to rigth.
 - Arrow DOWN    You move the pointer arrow to rigth if the angle is <= to 90, else to left.
 - ENTER	     Launch the bubble.


  Key values are written in PuzzleBOBS:ConfigFileBase, they are as raw codes and must be inserted
in decimal.




@endnode


@node MAIN_REQ "PuzzleBOBS guide - System requirements"

System requirements
-------------------


  PuzzleBOBS is a high, low level configurable game, this means that all machine resources are used
dinamically.
  For this reason is very hard to define the minimum requirements needed, above all about the
memory, because depends upon too many factors.
  However the game was tested on a lot of Amiga setups, on some A1200 unexpanded also, but using
graphic configurations with low resolutions. For this reason we can say that the minimum
requirement is:

  - 68020 processor
  - AmigaOS and roms in version 3.0
  - Almost 2 MB of mem
  - An HD with almost 10 MBytes free for the partial installation

  With this setups you can play to configuration as the 320*256 at 64 or 256 colours. To play to
higher configuration as the 800x600 at 16 millions colours you need more cpu power and memory.
  The ideal setup for PuzzleBOBS is:

  - 68040 or 68060 processor.
  - AmigaOS and roms in version 3.0
  - Graphic board with almost 4MB of videoram
  - 16 MBytes of fast memory.
  - An HD with almost 120 MBytes free for the full installation




@endnode


